2. Ancient papea—We know that many of Cicero's letters were written on the tablets described above, but lor the longer letters paper (charta) made from the papyrus plant was used. Pliny the Elder is our chief authority for the manufacture of the chartae. The pith oi the reed was cut into thin strips; these were laid side by side, and covered transversely ⁴with a similar layer. They were then wet with water, and perhaps with paste‚ pressed or hammered into a single sheet, and made smooth by pollshing. The size oi the charta depended upon the distance between successive joints of the papyrus reed. For writing on this substance, a pen (calmum) of reed, very like the quill pen of modern times, was used. The ink (atramentum) was made ot soot and gum, or from the juice of the cuttle-fish, and ¹ was thick like the ink of the Chinese. It could be removed with a sponge (spongia), and the charta thus cleaned was called a palimpsestas. In Fam. 7. 18. 2 Cicero asks Trebatius what writing could have been so worthless as to be replaced by the latter’s letter.
